04338nam a22006855i 9780292767973DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212000txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927679737 a10.7560/7873532doi  a(DE-B1597)588270  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF387 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a976.42211 aVeselka, Robert E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Courthouse Square in Texas /cRobert E. Veselka; ed. by Kenneth E. Foote. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tTables -- tForeword -- tChapter One. The Courthouse Square in Texas -- tChapter Two. From Land Policy to County Seats and Squares -- tChapter Three. Anglo-American Courthouse Squares -- tChapter Four. Origins of the Anglo-American Courthouse Squares -- tChapter Five. Squares Derived from Spanish Precedents and Other Planning Traditions -- tChapter Six. Origins of Squares Derived from Spanish Precedents and Other Planning Traditions -- tChapter Seven. The Centripetal Role of the Courthouse Square -- tChapter Eight. Symbolism and Social Activity at the Courthouse Square -- tChapter Nine. Afterword -- tAppendix 1. Texas Counties -- tAppendix 2 Block Patterns, Features, and Roles of Texas Courthouse Squares -- tAppendix 3. A Note on Sources and Methods -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith its dignified courthouse set among shade trees and lawns dotted with monuments to prominent citizens and fallen veterans, the courthouse square remains the civic center in a majority of the county seats of Texas. Yet the squares themselves vary in form and layout, reflecting the different town-planning traditions that settlers brought from Europe, Mexico, and the United States. In fact, one way to trace settlement patterns and ethnic dispersion in Texas is by mapping the different types of courthouse squares. This book offers the first complete inventory of Texas courthouse squares, drawn from extensive archival research and site visits to 139 of the 254 county seats. Robert Veselka classifies every existing plan by type and origin, including patterns and variants not previously identified. He also explores the social and symbolic functions of these plans as he discusses the historical and modern uses of the squares. He draws interesting new conclusions about why the courthouse square remains the hub of commercial and civic activity in the smaller county seats, when it has lost its prominence in others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCity and town lifezTexasxHistory. 0aCity planning - Texas - History. 0aCity planningzTexasxHistory. 0aCourthouseszTexasxDesign and constructionxHistory. 0aHuman geographyzTexas. 0aPlazaszTexasxDesign and constructionxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aFoote, Kenneth E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/78735340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292767973423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292767973/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK